*$F+F,F.F-" }{TEXT -1 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "2.  Polynomials:  " }{TEXT 303 20 "Intercepts and
 Sign." }{TEXT -1 192 "  There are several features about the graphs o
f polynomials which are important to track.  These features inform us \+
about the  behavior of the function.  Those features include the follo
wing:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
57 "    a.    x-intercepts of the function                   " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "                       Those values wher
e the graph crosses the x-axis.  Those points are solutions of the equ
ation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    regio
ns (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the f
unction are positive" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                \+
       Those regions where the graph lies above the x-axis.  For a con
tinuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are
 bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 
258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    c.    regions (intervals) in the domain \+
of the function where the values of the function are negative" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions whe
re the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in
 particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercep
ts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "
    d.   y-intercept of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 70 " \+
                      The value where the graph crosses the y-axis.  \+
" }{TEXT 316 37 "The value of the function when x = 0." }}{PARA 258 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "    e.   end limits" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
384 "                       For a polynomial, its values will become e
ither arbitrarily large in a positive sense or arbitrarily large in a \+
negative sense as the domain values tend to infinity.  Graphically, th
e values on the graph will growth arbitrarily large positively (go up \+
off the graph) or arbitrarily large negative (go down off the graph) a
s the domain values tend to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
87 "                       Similar behavior holds true for approaches \+
to negative infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 50 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a " }
{TEXT 305 5 "graph" }{TEXT -1 30 " of the polynomial.  Choose a " }
{TEXT 306 5 "range" }{TEXT -1 60 " that will optimally represent the f
eatures of the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 22 ", for each
 polynomial " }{TEXT 307 68 "find each of the above five graphcial cha
racteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
