{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "subs(x=0,d2);" }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"$G\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 132 "
The x intercepts are 2.0000 and 4.  The y intercept is 128.   d2 is po
sitive (-infinity,2) and (4,infinity).   d2 is negative (2,4)." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 42 "The end limits are up or positively large
." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "3. \+
 Polynomials:  Local extreme values and " }{TEXT 304 12 "monotonicity
" }{TEXT -1 159 ".  Beyond information of the type gathered above abou
t intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important information c
an be determined from the so called " }{TEXT 317 17 "\"critical points
\"" }{TEXT -1 19 " of a polynomial.  " }{TEXT 318 74 "The critical poi
nts of a polynomial are the intercepts of its derivative. " }{TEXT -1 
141 " Since the derivative of a function at a point represents the slo
pe of the tangent line to the graph of the that function at the point,
 then " }{TEXT 319 126 "the intercepts of the derivative are places wh
ere the the tangent lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizont
al lines. " }{TEXT -1 127 " At such places the graph is neither increa
sing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere the graph must be either increasing or
 decreasing.  " }{TEXT 308 123 "For a polynomial, local extreme values
 (local maximums or local minimums) must occur at the intercepts of th
e derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are important in analyzing the
 graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 258 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points of the function" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                      For a polynomial th
ese are the intercepts of the derivative of the polynomial" }}{PARA 
258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum points of the graph \+
of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "              \+
        These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which \+
the y-value is locally the largest value of the function.  Nearby valu
es on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point
 (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the graph of a functi
on y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                      Th
ese are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the y-valu
e is locally the smallest value of the function.  Nearby values on the
 graph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y) m
ust be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 108 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function w
here the values of the function are increasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 168 "                       Those regions where the graph ris
es as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a continuous fun
ction, and in particular for polynomials, " }{TEXT 327 5 "these" }
{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 328 42 "regions are bounded by the critical poin
ts" }{TEXT -1 33 " and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 259 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the f
unction where the values of the function are decreasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 168 "                       Those regions where the grap
